  "prompt": "What do the vacuoles in animal cells do?",
  "response": "In animal cells, vacuoles are small, membrane-bound organelles that perform various functions, although they are generally smaller and less prominent than those in plant cells. Here are some key roles of vacuoles in animal cells:\n\n1. **Storage**: Vacuoles can store essential substances, such as nutrients, ions, and waste products. They help maintain cellular homeostasis by regulating the levels of these substances.\n\n2. **Transport**: Vacuoles are involved in the transport of materials within the cell and can help in moving substances to different parts of the cell or potentially out of the cell.\n\n3. **Maintenance of Turgor Pressure**: While turgor pressure is more commonly associated with plant cells, some animal cells also utilize vacuoles to help regulate internal pressure, although this is less significant than in plant cells.\n\n4. **Digestion**: Some vacuoles, known as lysosomes, contain enzymes that break down macromolecules, old cell parts, and microorganisms. This process is important for cellular cleanup and recycling.\n\n5. **pH Regulation**: Vacuoles can help regulate the pH within the cell by storing acids or bases.\n\nIn general, while their functions in animal cells are not as pronounced as in plant cells (where large central vacuoles play crucial roles in maintaining cell structure and pressure), vacuoles in animal cells are still important for various aspects of cellular function and homeostasis.",
